{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> μηνίω</b>, <br /> <i>Doric dialect</i> <b>μᾱν-</b>, <i>future</i> -ῑσω [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"“Anthologia Graeca” 9.79 (1st c.AD: Leonidas Alexandrinus Epigrammaticus), -ιῶ LXX.Jer.3.12, +others: \">LXX+1st c.AD+</a>]<i>aorist</i> ἐμήνῑσα: (μῆνις):— <b>cherish wrath, be wroth against</b>, with <i>dative</i> <i>person</i>, μήνι᾽ Ἀχαιοῖσιν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.422; Ἀγαμέμνονι μήνιε δίῳ 18.257; Ἀθηναῖοι ὑμῖν μηνίουσι 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 9.7.β᾽, compare 5.84, 7.229:\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] with <i>genitive</i> _of things_, ἱρῶν μηνίσας <b>because of</b>.., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 5.178; πατρὶ μηνίσας φόνου 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 1177; ἔργου ἕκατι τοῦδε μ. [prev. author] “Tr.” 274; θεοῖς.. μηνίουσιν ἐς γένος [prev. author] “OC” 965: with _accusative_ _cognate_, οὐδ᾽ ἃ μηνίεις φράσας [prev. work] 1274: in 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] mostly <i>absolutely</i>, and of heroes, μήνι᾽ Ἀχιλλεύς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 12.10, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: rarely of common men, ὁ ξεῖνος δ᾽ εἴ περ μάλα μηνίει [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 17.14 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: <i>middle</i> in <i>active</i> sense, οὐδεὶς.. δαιμόνων μηνίεται [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Eumenides” 101.—poetical, 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus, 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus (only with reference to Homer, “Rh.” 1401b18, “APo.” 97b20)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>], and in later Prose, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" LXX (see. above), 1st c.BC: Diodorus Siculus Historicus 15.49, 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.775e, 2nd-3rd c.AD: Dio Cassius Historicus 72.9, etc.\">LXX+1st c.BC+</a>]; compare μηνιάω. [In <i>aorist</i> ῑ always: in <i>present</i> and <i>imperfect</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus uses ῑ in μήνῑεν 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.769 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>], and A. [prev. cited] in μηνῑετα; elsewhere [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] has μηνῐει, ἐμήνῐε, μήνῐ; [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] has μᾱνῐω in Lyric poetry, probably in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “Hipp.” 1146 \">Refs</a>]; μηνῐων in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “Rh.” 494.] \">Refs</a>]","strongNumber":"G8320","accentedUnicode":"μηνίω","shortDef":"be infuriated; cherish wrath","mediumDef":"be infuriated; cherish wrath","stepGloss":"be infuriated","stepTransliteration":"mēniō","count":0,"_step_Type":"verb","_stepDetailLexicalTag":"[[\"meaning\",\"G8320\",\"be infuriated\",0,\"μηνίω\"],[\"spelled\",\"G20730\",\"be wrathful\",0,\"μηνιάω\"]]"}]}